Answer: The problem is that you're calling `Iterator.next()` only once in your loop. This means that you're always getting the same `Shape` object from your `Iterator`. Therefore, when you call `printMe()`, you're always printing the same `Shape` object, regardless of the number in the `ArrayList`.

To fix this, you should call `Iterator.next()` for each iteration of your loop. Here's how you can do it:

```java
public void printShapes(ArrayList<String> numbers){
    Iterator<Shape> iter = this.shapes.iterator();
    for(String s:numbers){
        Shape shape = iter.next();
        shape.printMe(s);
    }
}
```

This way, you're always getting a new `Shape` object from your `Iterator`, and you're printing the correct one based on the current iteration.

Also, note that you don't need to use an `ArrayList` for `numbers`. You can use a `List` or an array, depending on your needs.

```java
List<String> numbers = Arrays.asList("1", "2", "3");
```

This will work just as well.

